---
import fs from 'node:fs';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

// Drop your photo at public/portrait.jpg and it appears automatically.
const hasPortrait = fs.existsSync(new URL('../../public/portrait.jpg', import.meta.url));
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About · Carey Manwa"
  description="Nairobi → EducationUSA → Cornell → computational social science. The longer story."
>
  <div class="col">
    <header class="article-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">About<span class="dot">·</span>Nairobi → Ithaca</span>
      <h1>About</h1>
    </header>

    {
      hasPortrait && (
        <figure class="portrait">
          <img
            src="/portrait.jpg"
            alt="Carey Manwa in a navy coat and patterned tie, smiling on a sunlit street"
            width="600"
            height="800"
            loading="eager"
          />
          <figcaption>ITHACA, NY</figcaption>
        </figure>
      )
    }

    <section class="reveal">
      <p>
        I grew up in Kenya, where I first understood that information doesn't
        distribute itself. As Lead Mentor at EducationUSA, the U.S. State
        Department's advising network, I led a team of 20 mentors into more
        than 30 Kenyan high schools, reaching over 20,000 students with
        something most of them had never been handed: a credible map of how to
        get to university abroad. The acting Deputy Chief of Mission at the
        U.S. Embassy in Nairobi gave us an award for it. I gave the work two
        years, and it gave me a path: I came to Cornell as one of the
        students that map was drawn for.
      </p>
      <p>
        At Cornell, the question behind that work got more precise. Who gets
        information, who believes it, and who acts on it isn't just a
        development problem; it's <em>the</em> problem, whether the actors
        are students in Nairobi, news readers in a polarized media market, or
        LLM agents in a simulated world. That's the thread connecting
        everything I do now: multi-agent simulations of social behavior at the
        <a href="/research/social-simulation/">Social Dynamics Lab</a>,
        persuasion-strategy classification across
        <a href="/research/persuasion-pipeline/">2M+ news articles</a>, and
        <a href="/research/disaster-resilience/">early-warning systems</a> that
        get information to humanitarian responders before disaster does.
      </p>
      <p>
        I work as an engineer because the questions demand it. The systems I
        study (media ecosystems, agent societies, disaster response) only
        open up to people who can build the instruments: scrapers that survive
        the open web, audit pipelines for agent behavior, satellite imagery
        pipelines, the web infrastructure of an
        <a href="/cv/">internationally-reaching research group</a> I've
        maintained since 2023.
      </p>
      <p>
        Outside the research: I teach (~300 Cornell students a semester,
        <a href="/teaching/">10/10 evaluations three semesters running</a>),
        and I led the hackathon-winning team in Cornell's SMART fellowship
        building <a href="/research/ecotourism-platform/">commerce
        infrastructure for East African ecotourism</a>, work that keeps me
        honest about who computational tools are ultimately for.
      </p>
      <p>
        If any of this overlaps with what you're working on, write to me:
        <a href="mailto:careyokal@gmail.com">careyokal@gmail.com</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
